es are increasingly used (and abused) in politics and social life. They have »many faces«, displays and interfaces. They occur as texts, recipes, stories, dramas in three acts, movies, videos, tweets, journeys of heroes, but also as rewarding stories in games and as narratives in society - such as a career from rags to riches, the concept of modernity or market economy. Below their surface, however, narrative mechanics are a particular type of motivational design - of game mechanics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aComputer Games. 4aCulture. 4aDigital Media. 4aGame Design. 4aGame Studies. 4aMedia Aesthetics. 4aMedia Studies. 4aMedia. 4aPopular Culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aComputer Games.  aCulture.  aDigital Media.  aGame Design.  aGame Studies.  aMedia Aesthetics.  aMedia Studies.  aMedia.  aPopular Culture.1 aAdams, Tarn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, René, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBöckler, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubbelman, Teun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaller, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlanagan, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlashüttner, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGötz, Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHack, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.